    <property>
      <description>When a person performs some action and presents a reason(s), and then an author praises the person, but uses different reason(s). The different reason(s) are not necessarily invalid, but if there's no evidence that the person performing the action did it because of that reason(s), he should not get credit.&#xd;
&#xd;
A classic example is the US invasion of Iraq, where the stated reason all along was to stop Iraq's WMD program. After it turned out there was no WMD program, people claimed that the invasion was a good thing because it killed Saddam Hussein, a brutal dictator.  That may certainly be a good result of the invasion, but it's not fair for someone to say "Bush did the right thing by invading Iraq to get rid of Saddam", or even "...because he got rid of Saddam", because that was never a stated goal.&#xd;
&#xd;
Often, a goal doesn't need to be stated. Say someone wants to start a business to "become a millionaire". She does so and makes a lot of money, but not a million. It's fair to say "that was a good decision", even though he didn't meet his stated goal. But in the case of something as major as a President invading another country, the goals are clearly stated, and if "kill Saddam Hussein" is not one of them, then it really was not a goal.</description>
    </property>
    <property>
      <example>Sean Hannity on his Apr 21, 2020 show, defended Trump's EO to suspend immigration because "We need to vet people, make sure that they don't have radical ties.", yet the EO and Trump never said anything about vetting, only jobs, and no additional vetting would be happening.</example>
